{"name": ["http://www.saultstar.com/2017/09/10/odd-couple-overcame-the-odds"], "content": ["Hidden Histories | Sault Star", "My account", "Change My Password", "Logout", "Search", "Autos", "Homes", "Careers", "Classified", "Obituaries", "Postmedia", "Saturday, November 25, 2017", "Sault Ste. Marie, ON", "-2\u00b0", "Overcast", "Fire \u2022\r\nWater \u2022\r\nStorm\r\n\r\nCLICK HERE!", "Home", "News", "Sports", "Entertainment", "Life", "Money", "Opinion", "Real Estate", "UR", "Marketplace", "Newsstand", "Contests", "Photos", "Videos", "Events", "Polls", "Weather", "International Bridge", "Galaxy Cinemas", "Playoff Pool", "Best of Sault Ste. Marie", "More", "Editorial", "Letters", "Column", "Opinion", "Column", "Odd couple overcame the odds", "By", "Karl Hele", "Sunday, September 10, 2017\n\t\t\t\t\t\t2:40:58 EDT PM", "Mary (Rice) and George Johnston. (Photos courtesy of the Chippewa County Historical Society, Sault Ste. Marie, Mich.)", "Tweet", "Change text size for the story", "Print", "Report an error", "GARDEN RIVER FIRST NATION\u00a0-", "In July 1839, the small Sault Ste Marie community was scandalized when a Baptist mission interpreter, Mary Rice, eloped with the \u201chalf-breed\u201d widower George Johnston. Both worked for the mission: Rice as a school teacher and Johnston as an occasional interpreter for the Rev. Abel Bingham.\u00a0 Rice was 36 and Johnston was 43 at the time of their marriage.\u00a0 Rice\u2019s untimely death on Sept. 25, 1858, of cancer left George to care for their four children. Johnston\u2019s health and lifestyle rapidly declined after Mary\u2019s death. He eventually froze to death on a walk in January 1861.", "George Johnston, born on April 10, 1796, spent most of his life in the Upper Great Lakes, other than an educational sojourn in Montreal. From his return to the Sault just before the outbreak of War in 1812 until his death in 1861, Johnston held a variety of government positions for the United States, Chippewa County, as well as Canada West such as interpreter, teacher, Indian agent, carpenter, and justice of the peace. Additionally, Johnston operated stores or trading posts for instance in the Sault region, Grand Traverse, and La Pointe. He also acted as a mineral speculator and part-time translator of sermons, hymns, and scripture for various missions in the Sault and Grand Traverse regions as well as for individuals seeking to communicate with the Anishinaabeg.", "Mary Rice was born on Oct. 31 1802 in Boston, Mass. Rice worked as a Baptist mission assistant from 1830 to 1834 in Sault Ste. Marie before being transferred to the Western Creek Nation mission.\u00a0 Here she worked from 1834 until 1836.\u00a0 Both transfers from the Sault mission to the Western Creek mission and back again were supposedly to alleviate health issues. Rev. Bingham initiated the first transfer claiming that he feared Rice had contracted tuberculosis. The move from the Creek station back to the Sault appears to have been initiated by Rice in an effort to escape from a situation that left her constantly ill and in care of the mission family. At both missions Rice worked as an assistant in the Sunday schools, teacher of the female day scholars, and general assistant in the mission houses. Judging from her correspondence, Rice was well educated, well liked, and committed to educating and Christianizing Indigenous peoples. Her faith and goals were also tempered by a loving humanity for the children the Indigenous parents placed in her care. Her employers often described her as being well liked, \u201cbright, capable and energetic.\u201d", "The Baptist mission to the Sault, launched in 1828 under the auspices of Rev. Abel Bingham, came into existence under the terms of the 1826 Treaty of Fond du Lac wherein the Anishinaabeg demanded a voluntary school be established at the Sault. The creation of the school and mission complex at the Sault led to a great need for mission assistants and teachers. As such, Rev. Bingham hired Mary Rice in 1830 to serve both as a domestic and instructress at the infant school. Like other employees of the mission, Rice set out to learn the Anishinaabeg language. During her employment at the mission from 1830 to 1834, Rice met and worked alongside Charlotte, Jane, and Eliza Johnston. Her friendships with the Johnston sisters would have allowed her to meet George Johnston when he was in the Sault.\u00a0 Stress, working conditions, and general ill health in the Sault region, caused Rice to become regularly ill by 1834, most often with a lung complaint. Bingham, concerned that Rice had contracted consumption, decided that she should work in a climate more suited to her condition.", "Interestingly, the more \u201csuitable climate\u201d chosen was in Georgia, which was also considered damp, changeable, and prone to consumption. Thus, I am left wondering if the transfer of Rice from one station to the next was a mask for something else.\u00a0 While it cannot be confirmed, George Johnston\u2019s first wife, Louisa Raymond Johnston, had died in 1832 leaving George in charge of three children, born in 1823, 1825, and 1827.\u00a0 Records indicate that George had a romantic interest that his family disapproved of in the early 1830s, around the time of his wife\u2019s death.\u00a0By 1832-1834, Bingham had a falling out with the Johnston family and sisters, which led to their withdrawal from the Baptist Church and eventual allegiance with the Methodists, Presbyterians, and Anglicans. Such a schism would have led to the withdrawal of friendships between the Johnstons and various Baptist mission employees and other supporters of Rev. Bingham. Perhaps Rice\u2019s transfer had more to do with a possible romance with George Johnston than a concern for consumption. Unfortunately, the records remain silent on the issue.", "Corresponding with\u00a0 Dr. Bolles of the American Baptist Foreign Mission Society (ABFMS) in December 1834, Rice requested a transfer from the Western Creek Mission station based on her continued ill health. Her letter indicates a great desire to leave as well as hope that she would continue to be useful to the ABFMS somewhere in a more accommodating eastern climate. The records unfortunately fail to indicate whether or not Rice maintained contact with the Johnston family.\u00a0Most likely she did not correspond with them based on the controversies of the early 1830s. Rice, however, appears to have maintained a correspondence with Bingham. The ABFMS returned Rice to the Sault in 1836 as an assistant in the school and mission house.", "At this point in 1836, George Johnston had once again become a resident of the Sault. He continued to work as an occasional interpreter and guide for Bingham, as well as other missionaries, Indian agents, and tourists in the area. Notwithstanding a lack of solid evidence for an earlier romance with George or continued correspondence with the Johnston sisters, Rice immediately renewed old friendships upon returning. Again, the records cannot tell us the details of Rice\u2019s and Johnston's courtship, although it does appear that Bingham disapproved of the intimate association between Rice and Johnston. This disapproval is what likely led to the couple slipping away from the Sault mission and travelling to Mackinaw Island where they were wed on July 16, 1839. Upon discovering that Rice had wed Johnston, Bingham wrote the ABFMS board expressing his disapproval and requesting direction. Prior to drafting the letter, however, Bingham had already dismissed Rice from her position and suspended her church membership. He likewise terminated George Johnston. Despite Bingham's disapproval and dire predictions for the match, Rice and Johnston were hired by the Michigan Superintendency of Indian Affairs, which their brother-in-law, Henry Rowe Schoolcraft, ran, to work at Grand Traverse as interpreters and model farmers. Rice was hired as an interpreter at a $300 per annum salary, which was in addition to Johnston\u2019s salary. After being dismissed from their posts apparently the (U.S. government objected to the apparent nepotistic hiring), George and Mary Johnston operated a trading establishment. The couple had four children: Benjamin Saurin (b.1840), James Laurence Kearney (b.1842), Samuel Abbott (b.1844), and Eliza Ann Jane (b.1846), who was named after George\u2019s three sisters. The three boys died in the U.S. Civil War, while Eliza lived into her 70s.", "Eventually the couple returned to the Sault in October 1846 and by 1849-1850 the couple opened a boarding house thereby taking advantage of the Sault\u2019s increasing stature as a tourist destination. William Benjamin Robinson stayed at the Johnston\u2019s boarding house while negotiating the Robinson-Huron and Robinson-Superior Treaties in 1850.\u00a0 By 1855, after the intercession of a friend, the couple rented the now empty Baptist mission buildings, which they renovated into a hotel/boarding house. The couple ran the boarding house until Mary\u2019s death in 1858. Thereafter, George was forced to remove from the old mission house, apparently for failing to pay rent for several years,\u00a0 and occupy empty barracks in U.S. Fort Brady with his young family.\u00a0Eliza, 12 at the time of her mother\u2019s death, was sent to live with Mary Rice Johnston\u2019s sister Hannah in 1858. She returned to the Sault in 1860 only to leave again after her father\u2019s death.", "Seemingly bereft after his wife\u2019s death, George increasingly corresponded with various individuals seeking indemnities for his involvement in the War of 1812, the destruction of his father\u2019s property in 1814, as well as various other claims and speculations. George died while on a walk one winter morning on Jan. 6, 1861 near the Sault canal by the rapids. Thus ended the story of a romance and elopement that shook the Sault in 1839.", "Karl S. Hele is an associate professor at Concordia University. He grew up north of Sault Ste. Marie and attended White Pines and Algoma University. His doctorate, from McGill in 2003, examined the Anishinaabe/missionary interaction in the Sault. His current work continues to explore the dynamics of the region\u2019s history. He is also a member of Garden River First Nation. karl.hele@bell.net.", "Featured Businesses", "Contact us to Advertise \u00bb", "Insurance", "Rivet Insurance", "Automotive", "Sudbury Fine Cars", "Home Improvement", "Handiman Clem", "Go to the Marketplace \u00bb", "Local Businesses", "Advertise with us", "Contribute", "Send Your Scoop!", "Share your story, photo or video about something you've seen.", "Send your story", "Subscription", "Start your day with Sault Star", "Choose among a variety of subscription packages and stay up to date with convenient home delivery and our on the go digital e-edition.", "View my options", "Sault Ste Marie", "View, submit, participate!", "Advertise", "Advertise online", "Announce your business", "Reach potential customers", "Contribute", "Send us news, photos or videos", "Add an event to the calendar", "Follow Sault Star", "Search", "News", "Local", "Provincial", "Canada", "World", "Sports", "High School Sports", "Local Hockey", "Hockey", "Basketball", "Baseball", "Football", "Soccer", "Curling", "Other Sports", "Playoff Pool", "Entertainment", "Local", "Movies", "Music", "Television", "Celebrities", "Life", "Health", "Food", "Travel", "Opinion", "Editorial", "Letters", "Column", "UR", "Entertainment", "Life", "Money", "News", "Opinion", "Sports", "Money", "Real Estate", "Marketplace", "Newsstand", "Contests", "Photos", "Videos", "Events", "Polls", "Weather", "International Bridge", "Galaxy Cinemas", "Playoff Pool", "Best of Sault Ste. Marie", "Subscribe", "Print", "E-Edition", "Advertise", "Online", "Print", "Sault Star", "Feedback", "Letters to the editor", "Postmedia Publications", "Where to buy", "Services", "Autos", "Canoe", "Careers", "Classifieds", "Homes", "Obituaries", "Sitemap", "Pr