{"name": ["http://punemirror.indiatimes.com/others/you/love-is-all-they-need/articleshow/61647531.cms"], "content": ["Love is all they need - Pune Mirror", "Pune Mirror", "Ad Blocker Detected", "We have noticed that you have an ad blocker enabled which restricts ads served on the site.", "Please disable it to continue reading", "Pune Mirror", "Steps for disabling ad blocker", "Home", "Steps for disabling ad blocker", "Refresh", "WELCOME,", "My Times", "LOGOUT", "SIGN IN", "Mumbai Mirror", "|", "Bangalore Mirror", "|", "Ahmedabad Mirror", "Home", "Pune", "Pune Speaks", "Cover Story", "Crime", "Civic", "Others", "Campus", "Entertainment", "Bollywood", "Hollywood", "Film Reviews", "Unwind", "Marathi Reviews", "Columns", "Aside", "The Informer", "Talk Back", "Columnists", "News", "India", "World", "Sports", "Cricket", "Others", "Photos", "Entertainment", "Sports", "News", "Cartoon & Kidzone", "Videos", "Cricbuzz", "Travel", "All", "Leisure", "Sunday Read", "Scitech", "You", "Special", "Eat", "Home", "Others", "You", "Love is all they need", "By\u00a0SOWMYA RAJARAM and Vidya Iyengar", "SOWMYA RAJARAM and Vidya Iyengar", "|", "Updated: Nov 19, 2017, 10.03 PM IST", "Print this article", "Reduce font size", "Increase font size", "My Saved articles", "Whatsapp", "Facebook", "Google Plus", "Twitter", "Email", "Linkedin", "SMS", "Share", "Whatsapp", "Facebook", "Google Plus", "Twitter", "Email", "Linkedin", "SMS", "Ayush Bhambhani, who is 19, with his family( PICS: MUTHU P AND KAUSHIK JN);   (inset) Kavita Dambal with her son Anmol", "Raising a child with special needs requires much acceptance, patience and perseverance. Parents of children with developmental disorders on how one copes", "Nine-year-old Vivaan\u2019s first word was iPad. A child\u2019s first word is always special for a parent, but for VR Ferose and wife Deepali Kulkarni, it was more than just that. Diagnosed with autism when he was 18 months old, Vivaan is mostly non-verbal. So \u2018iPad\u2019 merited \u2014 like Vivaan\u2019s other milestones: first day in school, first school performance, first birthday \u2014 a small celebration. As parents of a child with special needs, Ferose (a senior VP with a global IT firm) and his wife have gone through denial, depression, pain before arriving at acceptance and joy. But it has been an arduous journey \u2014 like it is for all those parenting children with special needs. Dealing with the news that one\u2019s child is born with a neurodevelopmental disorder can be challenging for any parent.", "For Kavita Dambal, mother to 19-year-old Anmol (who was initially misdiagnosed with ADHD and later diagnosed with autism at age four-and-a-half), the shock was so severe that she went into depression. \u201cI stopped eating for a couple of months,\u201d she says, admitting that she was resentful and unable to come to terms with reality. Limited awareness about the condition in the late \u201990s only made things worse. \u201cSo we had to learn with him,\u201d says the former high court lawyer who now works with her son at a paper bag unit founded by her.", "Grappling with social situations", "Dambal recalls how, as a young boy, Anmol used to get into fights with children from the neighbourhood and get agitated around his younger brother. \u201cIt used to upset me no end,\u201d she says. Twelve-year-old Ayan Dogra\u2019s mother Shweta even considered giving up public outings. Shweta remembers that her son would settle down on the floor and start yelling and tear up thermocol. Both mothers, however, decided that avoiding public spaces and situations was not a solution. \u201cI realised that as soon as I explained the situation to people, they were understanding,\u201d Dambal says, while Dogra decided to not try to control her son and also became more vocal about his condition. \u201cWe\u2019ve never hidden the fact that he\u2019s autistic,\u201d says the former publicist-turnedhomemaker. Sometimes, she tells visitors to postpone their visits because Ayan is going through a \u201crough phase\u201d. \u201cSometimes, he\u2019s not in a good mood and doesn\u2019t like anyone coming home. He\u2019s also going through hormonal changes. So why torture him with things he\u2019s not comfortable with?\u201d", "Preeti Bhambhani, whose 19-year-old son Ayush was diagnosed with the condition at age two, agrees that parents need to be more accepting and less controlling. While Bhambhani had the support of her husband, parents and daughter in raising their son, who is now an artist and a foodie, she feels that \u201cthose who aren\u2019t empathetic [to her son\u2019s condition], aren\u2019t worth it\u201d. Bhambhani lost friends and relatives because \u201cthey were insensitive to his condition\u201d, and doesn\u2019t regret it.", "Life alterations", "Parenting a child with special needs necessitates a lifestyle overhaul. From being a cloistered person who \u201cwouldn\u2019t even go down to the market to buy groceries alone\u201d, Bhambhani learnt to ride a scooter to accompany her son Ayush to therapy, school and everywhere in between. Ferose recalls how he was a rising young star, becoming one of the youngest chief executives in India at the age of 33, a post he held for over five years. \u201cJuggling work, travel, doctor visits, therapies and the desire to lead a normal life was overwhelming,\u201d he says. His wife, who worked part time for a couple of years when Vivaan was younger, has since been a stay-at-home mom to care for Vivaan, which Ferose feels \u201cis more than a full time job\u201d. \u201cI think going to work is like taking a vacation compared to staying home to take care of home and family. We all have our own coping mechanisms. My wife copes by throwing herself completely into bringing up Vivaan,\u201d he says.", "Their social life is constrained, despite their best effort. Going for dinner or movies can be challenging. \u201cHaving friends who understand the condition and are flexible makes it easier. The numerous therapies and doctor visits get taxing. But it is the slow pace of progress that tires you. Taking a regular break to unwind is mandatory for our sanity,\u201d says Ferose, who loves reading and writing. A pursuit that was triggered by Vivaan\u2019s condition was curating the India Inclusion Summit, an egalitarian platform, which brings together global thought leaders working in the field of inclusion to deliberate, discuss and take forward different talents available in the society. He also co-authored Gifted, a book of inspiring stories of those with disabilities. Four years ago, the family moved to California so that Vivaan attend a regular school.", "Bhambhani has often ignored stares and whispers as Ayush lay prostrate in the middle of a shopping mall, throwing a tantrum. She\u2019s also pulled him out of schools that claimed to be inclusive and integrated, but locked him up in a room. She taught him the difference between night and day by taking him for a walk in the middle of the night to physically show him that establishments are shut and that he can\u2019t go shopping or watch a movie at that time. She has endured 20-minute-long teeth brushing rituals, while he learns to do it on his own. It has meant changing their lifestyle to always ensure that one parent is at home no matter what. But importantly, she has also ensured that her younger daughter doesn\u2019t feel neglected because of the extra attention that Ayush demands.", "Seeking help", "The first and most important support system has to be the family and Bhambhani\u2019s parents have been open-minded, involved and accepting of Ayush\u2019s situation. But to be able to care and comfort correctly, counselling is imperative. Sarbani Mallick, founder-director and managing trustee, Bubbles Centre for Autism and Pragati Vocational Skill Centre, says mothers confide in her that they cannot even get a minute off for themselves \u2014 sometimes not even being able to afford the privacy for a change during their period. \u201cThey are so worried about what the child will do in their absence; they have no peace of mind. A few days ago, I came across a mother who wanted to kill her child. The other parents we counsel are mostly in denial and come to us two years post-diagnosis at the earliest.\u201d Mallick also makes home visits, which helps her assess the situation for both child and parent. \u201cThe problem is complex. Many children appear fine physically, so it becomes harder for parents to accept that their child has a problem. And then, there\u2019s the blame game at home to figure out what went wrong. For many parents, life comes to a halt. And going for counselling only reaffirms that their child has a problem. So, they hesitate asking for help.\u201d", "But quality intervention can change lives. How else would", "Unabashedly Ayush", ", a book chronicling Ayush\u2019s journey, woven through his artworks, put together by creative agency Pink Lemonade, have been possible? Ayush\u2019s transition from someone who couldn\u2019t brush his teeth or tie his laces, to a boy who is independent and can command art shows with the sheer velocity of his work, is an inspiring story. But none of it would have been possible without the support and perseverance of his mother, something even Tina Garg, Founder & CEO of Pink Lemonade acknowledges. Like the proverbial woman in every successful man\u2019s life, Bhambhani, supported by her family and the staff at Sense Kaleidoscopes (Ayathi Trust), which works with autistic children, has been the force behind Ayush\u2019s growth. Encouraged by his teachers at Ayathi Trust, she put together the book on his journey \u201cto chronicle his artistic streak as well as build awareness about the condition,\u201d Garg says. The coffee table book is packed with vivid drawings, interactive pop-up elements such as magnets, shoes that can have laces tied through them, foldable pages and shapes and much more. All in a bid to showcase the incredible depth and breadth of Ayush\u2019s thought process, and his willingness to live life by his own rules.", "Learning to cope", "There are rewards too. Not comparing Vivaan to other kids has been his parents\u2019 key to happiness. \u201cVivaan will turn nine years old soon and he is our life. As our only child, he is normal to us even if he is labelled as a child with autism. Our coping mechanism has been to treat him like every other child and we are still learning every day. Being mostly non-verbal, he remains a mystery to us. We are always trying to guess what\u2019s going on in his mind. Even now, he surprises us every day \u2014 he knows a lot more than what we think he knows. He is a happy child and has spread a lot of happiness around him,\u201d Ferose says. \u201cAnd he is the favourite of all his teachers.\u201d", "Today, Bhambhani believes", "Unabashedly Ayush", "will be an invaluable tool for parents and persons working with autistic children. The litmus test is that it has been loved by Ayush. How do we know that? Because when she showed him the book, he gave her a spontaneous kiss and a hug, the instances of which she can \u201ccount on fingers\u201d. In that sense, Ayush\u2019s journey, and his successes, are Preeti\u2019s too.", "\u2588 We all have our own coping mechanisms. My wife copes by throwing herself completely into bringing up Vivaan", "\u2014 V R Ferose", "GALLERIES", "View more photos", "Maharashtra vs Karnataka Ranji Day 1", "In Pics: India vs New Zealand 2nd ODI in Pune, New Zealand bats", "Tulsibaug Ganpati", "Pune Celebrates Onam", "Pune festival: Inaugural Function", "Ganesh Chaturthi 2017: Immersion at Pune", "Most Read", "TODAY", "THIS WEEK", "MONTH", "ALL TIME", "Across Pune Mirror >>", "Kapil Sharma's film Firangi stuck at th...", "Kapil Sharma's film Firangi stuck at the censors", "Live Updates: Bigg Boss 11, Episode 54,...", "Live Updates: Bigg Boss 11, Episode 54, Day 54, 24th November 2017 Luxury Budget speci