{"name": ["http://punemirror.indiatimes.com/others/sunday-read/a-song-for-kathmandu/articleshow/61166915.cms"], "content": ["A song for Kathmandu - Pune Mirror", "Pune Mirror", "Ad Blocker Detected", "We have noticed that you have an ad blocker enabled which restricts ads served on the site.", "Please disable it to continue reading", "Pune Mirror", "Steps for disabling ad blocker", "Home", "Steps for disabling ad blocker", "Refresh", "WELCOME,", "My Times", "LOGOUT", "SIGN IN", "Mumbai Mirror", "|", "Bangalore Mirror", "|", "Ahmedabad Mirror", "Home", "Pune", "Pune Speaks", "Cover Story", "Crime", "Civic", "Others", "Campus", "Entertainment", "Bollywood", "Hollywood", "Film Reviews", "Unwind", "Marathi Reviews", "Columns", "Aside", "The Informer", "Talk Back", "Columnists", "News", "India", "World", "Sports", "Cricket", "Others", "Photos", "Entertainment", "Sports", "News", "Cartoon & Kidzone", "Videos", "Cricbuzz", "Travel", "All", "Leisure", "Sunday Read", "Scitech", "You", "Special", "Eat", "Home", "Others", "Sunday Read", "A song for Kathmandu", "By\u00a0Lalitha Suhasini", "Lalitha Suhasini", ", Pune Mirror", "|", "Updated: Oct 22, 2017, 04.29 PM IST", "Print this article", "Reduce font size", "Increase font size", "My Saved articles", "Whatsapp", "Facebook", "Google Plus", "Twitter", "Email", "Linkedin", "SMS", "Share", "Whatsapp", "Facebook", "Google Plus", "Twitter", "Email", "Linkedin", "SMS", "Suman Kulkarni (centre) plays one of the leads in the three-hour long musical; (below) Sandip Varkey George and Kulkarni at a rehearsal ;  PICS: MANOJ BIDKAR", "A new musical, scripted by academic John Mathew, is an ambitious exploration of Nepal\u2019s turbulent political history and features over 70 students from the city-based Indian Institute of Science Education and Research", "At once personal and far reaching, the musical,", "The Sun Was White; The Moon Disobedient", ",", "begins with news of the massacre of 2001 at Narayanhity Palace in Nepal. At the centre of the production is Brian Houghton Hodgson, a British naturalist based in India and Nepal in 1837, a character that has inspired its scriptwriter and director, Dr John Mathew, who currently teaches at the Indian Institute of Science Education and Research, Pune (IISER), Pune. \u201cHe\u2019s fascinating,\u201d says Mathew of Hodgson, \u201cThe chap knew Nepali, Newari, Tibetan. He studied Tibetan architecture, ethnography and wrote some 100 papers on Indian birds and mammals. All the while, he was involved in palace intrigue.\u201d When we watch Hodgson on stage during a rehearsal, it\u2019s his voice that makes heads turn. Sandip Varkey George, a PhD student from the physics department, is researching chaos theory when he isn\u2019t working his impressive baritone on stage. \u201cNewbies are rather well encouraged to join theatre here,\u201d says George, who adds that he was intimidated by the theatre scene during his undergrad days at Delhi University, \u201cThis is my first major show at IISER. I barely made the cut during my first audition, but my second audition went well.\u201d", "Since early this year, over 70 students at IISER, Pune, comprising cast or crew have been working on", "The Sun Was White; The Moon Disobedient", ",", "and describe it as the most ambitious project that they have taken up at the institute. \u201cI\u2019ve never done theatre before, but last semester, John had a course on \u2018Science, History and Theatre\u2019, which was my introduction to theatre. What surprised me about this production was the scale of it and the talent that we have here at IISER,\u201d says production director, Shraddha Lall, who is a student of the BSMS (Biology) programme at the institute. That Hodgson creates the axis around which both the present and the past revolve, is the most interesting aspect for Lall, who has studied evolutionary biology and has closely followed Hodgson\u2019s work. \u201cHow Hodgson transcends through time, the parallels that we see in politics and how Hodgson and Manjushree relate to each other across centuries shows how history can be important in ways that you cannot imagine,\u201d adds Lall. Mathew, who has a PhD from Harvard University on the history of science that focused on late eighteenth to early twentieth century naturalists in India, has been researching the subject for a few years now. \u201cHodgson is a complicated character,\u201d says Mathew, \u201cHe takes up with this aristocratic Kashmiri woman or a dhobini (named Meharunnisha in the play). I\u2019ve gone with the dhobini story because it just made it more interesting for me. Amritananda, a priest of the Vajracharyas, which is a non-celibate group of monks, helped him with Buddhist texts and was rumoured to have had an affair with Meharunnisha before he introduced him to Hodgson. But I draw attention to that situation in a song-out if you will.\u201d", "All original songs in the musical, which also features standards such as \u201cI\u2019m Beginning To See The Light\u201d by jazz legend, Ella Fitzgerald, have been composed by Mathew. \u201cI really want us to do musicals,\u201d he says, \u201cAndrew Lloyd Weber\u2019s", "Jesus Christ Superstar", "keeps getting done. Lovely music, but can\u2019t we write ours? We\u2019ve got talent, so let\u2019s do it.\u201d Srikrishna Sekhar, the musical director of", "The Sun Was White; The Moon Disobedient", "is one such promising guitarist that Mathew has roped in for the production. \u201cI\u2019ve worked on several other plays, but I\u2019ve never worked with a group that\u2019s this big. It\u2019s usually me and one more musician creating music that is used in the background,\u201d says 26-year-old Sekhar, a PhD student of astrophysics, \u201cBut here, we\u2019re accompanying the singers, so it\u2019s like a supporting role for us.\u201d While Sekhar is in charge of a seven-member band of musicians, the ensemble backing the cast also includes an 11-member choir. \u201cWe are doing a lot of harmonies because that\u2019s the one thing that audiences are not used to in India and we\u2019ve worked on about 20 songs,\u201d says Abhinaya V, another PhD student and the vocal director for", "The Sun Was White; The Moon Disobedient", ".", "The musical also includes a popular Nepali folk song titled \u201cResamm Firiri\u201d, except that it has been transformed into a blues song.", "Mathew, who has spent close to nine years on bringing", "The Sun Was White; The Moon Disobedient", "to life, spares no effort in recreating the socio-political landscape in Nepal down to the last detail. For instance, the Bhaad-gaaule topi worn by the penultimate monarch of the country, King Dipendra Bir Bikram Shah, is all black, unlike the more colourful Dhaka topi worn by ministers. For a production that is a debut musical for most of the cast and crew, the ambition is Himalayan-sized. \u201cIf we fail, we\u2019ll ensure we fail spectacularly,\u201d says Mathew.", "The Sun Was White; The Moon Disobedient", "will be staged on October 27 at 8 pm and October 28 at 12 pm at the CV Raman Auditorium at IISER, Pune", "\u2588 I really want us to do musicals. Andrew Lloyd Weber\u2019s Jesus Christ Superstar keeps getting done. Lovely music, but can\u2019t we write ours? We\u2019ve got talent, so let\u2019s do it", "\u2014 Dr John Mathew, faculty, IISER, Pune", "GALLERIES", "View more photos", "Maharashtra vs Karnataka Ranji Day 1", "In Pics: India vs New Zealand 2nd ODI in Pune, New Zealand bats", "Tulsibaug Ganpati", "Pune Celebrates Onam", "Pune festival: Inaugural Function", "Ganesh Chaturthi 2017: Immersion at Pune", "Most Read", "TODAY", "THIS WEEK", "MONTH", "ALL TIME", "Across Pune Mirror >>", "Kapil Sharma's film Firangi stuck at th...", "Kapil Sharma's film Firangi stuck at the censors", "Live Updates: Bigg Boss 11, Episode 54,...", "Live Updates: Bigg Boss 11, Episode 54, Day 54, 24th November 2017 Luxury Budget special: Will Bigg Boss grant points to housemates tonight?", "D