{"name": ["http://nationalpost.com/life/food/get-a-taste-of-brazil-with-recipes-for-codfish-cakes-and-caipirinha-cocktail"], "content": ["Get a taste of Brazil: Recipes for codfish cakes and caipirinha cocktail to put you in the Olympic mood | National Post", ".widget_twitter li {\n\tword-wrap: break-word;\n}", "Sign In/Register", "Subscribe", "Search NationalPost.com ...", "News", "All News", "National", "World", "Toronto", "Politics", "Full Comment", "Sports", "All Sports", "NHL", "All NHL", "Vancouver Canucks", "Calgary Flames", "Edmonton Oilers", "Winnipeg Jets", "Toronto Maple Leafs", "Ottawa Senators", "Montreal Canadiens", "Baseball", "Basketball", "NBA", "NCAA", "Football", "CFL", "NFL", "Soccer", "Golf", "Golf Videos", "Tennis", "Olympics", "Culture", "All Culture", "Books", "Celebrity", "Movies", "Music", "Theatre", "Television", "Life", "All Life", "Health", "Homes", "Eating & Drinking", "Style", "Travel", "Life By Design", "Parenting", "More", "Horoscopes", "Contests", "Driving", "Classifieds", "Jobs", "Subscribe", "Financial Post", "Get a taste of Brazil: Recipes for codfish cakes and caipirinha cocktail to put you in the Olympic mood", "A favourite appetizer found in Rio de Janeiro is bolinhos de bacalhau, or codfish cakes, with bars, street stalls and markets all offering their version", "A favourite appetizer found in Rio de Janeiro is bolinhos de bacalhau, or codfish cakes, with bars, street stalls and markets all offering their version.", "The Canadian Press", "August 10, 2016", "9:47 AM EDT", "Filed under", "Eating & Drinking", "Comment", "Facebook", "Twitter", "Reddit", "Email", "More", "Share this story", "Get a taste of Brazil: Recipes for codfish cakes and caipirinha cocktail to put you in the Olympic mood", "Tumblr", "Pinterest", "Google Plus", "LinkedIn", "TORONTO \u2014 While enjoying a savoury snack from one of the numerous vendors along Rio\u2019s famous Copacabana Beach won\u2019t be an option for most Canadians during", "this month\u2019s Olympics", ", there are plenty of ways to sample Brazilian flavours at home.", "Hearty feijoada, which is redolent with smoked pork and hot Brazilian peppers, and churassco, or grilled meats, are just a couple of the South American country\u2019s signature dishes.", "Brazil has a wide array of regional cuisines, with influences from indigenous people as well as Europeans \u2014 especially Portuguese, Italians and Germans \u2014 along with Africans and Japanese, says Mario Cassini, a Toronto-based chef who\u2019s passionate about sharing the culture of his Brazilian homeland with authentic dishes.", "Cassini began learning to cook as a child with his grandfather, who emigrated from Portugal, and his aunt.", "\u201cI remember he got this huge codfish and he boiled that thing and then he got the kids to take the pieces from the bone by hand from the huge carcass,\u201d Cassini recalls. Then he made Bacalhau a Gomes de Sa, a baked casserole of cod, boiled potatoes, peppers, sauteed onions, black olives and olive oil.", "Galit Rodan/The Canadian Press", "The Portuguese are famous for their seafood dishes and that, combined with Rio\u2019s location on the ocean, means that fried, grilled or stewed fish and seafood like mussels sauteed in garlic and olive oil or shrimp in bouillabaisse are popular, says Cassini, who hails from Belo Horizonte in Minas Gerais state, south of Rio, and now works on consulting projects in Toronto under his Global Culinary Concepts company.", "Another traditional dish is moqueca, which originated as fish wrapped in a banana leaf and steamed in a firepit. Cooks in Espirito Santos, north of Rio, adapted the recipe from the native people to create a stew, which Cassini makes with fish, paprika, turmeric, onions, peppers, fish broth and cilantro or parsley.", "But it is feijoada, a black bean stew with pork, beef and sausage, that is especially beloved by the locals in Rio.", "\u201cI think everywhere in Brazil if you ask what is your favourite dish they\u2019re going to say feijoada,\u201d says Cassini, who featured it for a decade at his Toronto restaurant Caju.", "\u201cIt\u2019s an art to make the feijoada, a labour of love. It\u2019s a whole culture behind even making it.\u201d", "Galit Rodan/The Canadian Press", "He soaks the beans for a day and carefully carves the beef and pork into pieces, which he marinates in garlic and red wine. In his version, he adds smoked chorizo and pork hock for depth of flavour and uses malagueta peppers for seasoning.", "\u201cThough they\u2019re hot, they\u2019re not too intense to take over the dish,\u201d says Cassini.", "The dish is topped with farofa, a toasted cassava flour mixture sauteed with onions, olive oil and garlic. It looks like coarse sand and adds a distinct texture to the dish.", "White rice and collard greens sauteed in garlic and olive oil are common side dishes with feijoada, which is washed down with shots of the sugarcane spirit cachaca.", "People love the root cassava, or mandioca, sliced and fried.", "\u201cIt tastes better than french fries. It\u2019s healthier,\u201d notes Cassini, who also purees it to top a version of shepherd\u2019s pie filled with flank steak.", "Restaurants specializing in churrasco, or grilled beef, pork, sausage or chicken, feature waiters bringing selections on skewers to the tables and slicing off as much as one can eat.", "Galit Rodan/The Canadian Press", "Grilling is a social occasion in neighbourhoods and parks on weekends too.", "\u201cPeople gather around the barbecue guy. It\u2019s like a party,\u201d with music and shots of cachaca adding to the atmosphere, says Cassini.", "A prized cut of beef in Brazil is picanha, or top sirloin cap. When grilling, cooks simply sprinkle rock salt on meat \u2014 the secret to the flavour is the marbling, or fat, says Cassini.", "Visitors might also sample picadinho, another well-known dish, which is hand-chopped beef seasoned and cooked in a brown sauce (like stroganoff without the cream). It can be served with rice and/or fries and topped with a poached or fried egg.", "Locals also have a passion for black beans, rice and potatoes prepared the Portuguese way \u2014 sliced, then fried. In Rio, salads using hearts of palm are very popular as are leafy green salads with tomatoes.", "Ingredients from the Amazon also inspire chefs around the country, who use the abundance of fresh fruit and vegetables, herbs and roots in inventive ways.", "With Brazil being the world\u2019s largest coffee producer, Portuguese corner bakeries selling coffee along with such popular desserts as quindim, a baked custard with coconut, and mousse de maracuja (passionfruit mousse) are also common.", "Brazil\u2019s national cocktail poised for Olympic exposure", "Canadian author revisits Portuguese home cooking", "Learn how to better slice and dice your way through summer", "BOLINHOS DE BACALHAU (Codfish Cakes)", "500 g (1 lb) salted codfish", "1 sweet or other type of onion, chopped", "30 ml (2 tbsp) olive oil, for sauteing onions", "2 large white potatoes, peeled and cubed (about 300 g/10 oz)", "1 bay leaf", "1 egg, separated", "125 ml (1/2 cup) chopped parsley or cilantro", "Salt, to taste", "500 ml (2 cups) vegetable oil, for frying (approx)", "fresh limes and hot sauce, for serving", "1.", "Soak salted codfish overnight, changing the water at least 3 times. Drain, remove any bones and skin, and cut in small chunks.", "2.", "In a skillet, heat olive oil; saute onion until soft and set aside. (This can be done ahead.)", "3.", "In a medium pot, place potatoes and cover with water. Add bay leaf. Bring water to a simmer and cook potatoes until soft. Add codfish pieces and cook for 5 minutes. Remove from heat and let stand for 5 minutes. Strain potatoes and codfish, discarding water and bay leaf.", "4.", "In a large bowl, mash together potatoes and codfish until well mixed. Mix in sauteed onion. Add egg yolk and continue to mix. Beat egg white until foamy and fold into mixture. Add parsley and mix well. Taste and add salt, if needed.", "5.", "Refrigerate codfish cake mixture for at least 30 minutes or overnight.", "6.", "Just before frying, remove cod cake mixture from fridge. If mixture is too moist, cod cakes may fall apart or not brown properly when frying. Add a bit of flour to absorb excess moisture and mix well. Use 2 tablespoons to shape cod cake mixture into quenelles (egg shape with slightly rounded points) or croquettes: scoop some of the mixture onto a spoon, then gently press scooped mixture with bowl of second spoon to compress, and smooth edges.", "7.", "Meanwhile, preheat vegetable oil over medium-high heat in a skillet or pot deep enough so that oil covers cod cakes. Using a large spoon, carefully lower cod cakes into oil. Do not overcrowd pot. Fry until golden brown, about 5 minutes (depending on the temperature of the oil). Using a slotted spoon, carefully remove cod cakes from oil, letting oil drip off. Place on paper towel to absorb excess oil.", "8.", "Serve with fresh limes and hot sauce.", "makes 12 to 15 cod cakes (depending on size)", "Source: Chef Mario Cassini, Global Culinary Concepts.", "CAIPIRINHA", "This drink is regarded as Brazil\u2019s national cocktail. Its base is a clear spirit known as cachaca that is distilled from fresh sugarcane juice. Some imbibers equate the drink to a mojito without the mint.", "1 lime", "10 ml (2 tsp) granulated sugar, or to taste", "60 ml (2 oz) cachaca", "crushed or chopped ice", "lime slices, for garnish", "1.", "Slice a couple of rounds from the lime to garnish the glass. Chop remainder.", "2.", "To a shaker, add chopped lime and sugar. Mash together with a muddler or wooden spoon. Add cachaca and ice and shake until well mixed. Pour into an old-fashioned glass. Add more ice and garnish glass with lime rounds.", "makes 1 serving", "Source: Chef Mario Cassini, Global Culinary Concepts.", "0", "Comments", "Share your thoughts", "News Videos", "Latest Food", "Watch",