eed to sign a giving pledge now? Is it to publicly show that you are committed to giving back?", "Rohini Nilekani:", "We have been talking about this for a while, but it took me, more than Nandan, some time to agree to publicly declare this. Not because we were not planning to give away so much of our", "wealth", ". We always were. But it isn\u2019t easy to give it away, and I felt that now is the time when Nandan also has more time to focus on this. It requires both of us to be able to do it well.", "We have matured over the years, and we can now work strategically to do it better. So, we felt the timing was right to make the pledge.", "Q. Why the decision to sign the pledge after returning to the corporate sector?", "Nandan Nilekani:", "That is just a coincidence. This has been in the works for several months now. As Rohini said, I think what the giving pledge has done is that it has also brought together a set of philanthropists, and that creates a forum where you can share the best practices. A forum where you can collaborate over larger social issues. In that sense, it is a very effective forum, and that is as valuable as saying that we have just signed the pledge. Giving was already part of our DNA. It has always been there. But this was a way to become part of a group that was looking at the same kind of problems worldwide.", "Talking philanthropy:", "Bill Gates", "in conversation with Rohini and Nandan Nilekani. (Image: BCCL)", "Rohini Nilekani:", "To add to that, the one thing that we keep saying in India is that our culture is not to show that we give. But I feel that signalling is also important. If you are going to be super wealthy you will have to be super generous as well, and I think that signalling matters.", "Q. You are, in a way, giving away half of your children\u2019s inheritance. Was there a conversation with them about this?", "Rohini Nilekani:", "To begin with, we do not fully believe that this wealth belongs to us. To be honest, both Nandan and I feel that we have been very lucky. A lot of luck is involved in creating so much wealth, and so we definitely feel that we are trustees of this, and not owners. The children have known this from the beginning, and they too are very interested in big ideas and philanthropy. There was never any question of them feeling entitled to the wealth. They have been fully supportive, hence, it has been an easy decision for us.", "Q. How has the meaning of money evolved for you over the years?", "Nandan Nilekani:", "I think money, after a point, is just about the choices it brings. It gives you the flexibility to address issues. So, in essence, the power to give away is the most important value of money, because beyond a point your personal needs are well taken care of.", "0", "Comments", "Want stories like this in your inbox? Sign up for the weekly ET Panache", "newsletter", ".", "You can also follow us on", "Facebook", ",", "Twitter", "and", "LinkedIn", ".", "Read more on", "Wealth", "rohini nilekani", "Nandan Nilekani", "Infosys Nandan Nilekani", "Infosys", "Giving Pledge", "Bill Gates", "Also Read", "Infosys to open innovation hubs in the US: Nandan Nilekani", "'Nandan Nilekani can provide stability\u2019", "Aadhaar will come out with flying colours: Nandan Nilekani", "Nandan Nilekani: Aadhaar architect set to turn peacemaker", "Fund managers pitch for Nandan Nilekani's return to Infosys", "Comments", "Add Your Comments", "More From Panache", "1/20", "So, who was Padmavati?", "That was some Thanksgiving! Fake Google ad sends users to scam site", "Can playing football be dangerous to your health in the long run? Science says, yes", "Twisty Board 2 is the kind of fun arcade game that everyone will enjoy", "Umang, the app that allows access Indian Government's services through web and mobile", "In a bid to maintain exclusivity, Chanel will not move to online sales any time soon", "'Coco' review: Pixar's roller coaster-ride of emotions will cast a spell on you", "From FedE